00:42:12.920 --> 00:42:15.780
So this is just a little
excerpt of the menu.

00:42:15.780 --> 00:42:18.820
Coming from Roman Spitalfields
going through Hungry

00:42:18.820 --> 00:42:19.370
Spitalfields.

00:42:19.370 --> 00:42:23.050
I literally served a dish of
nothing and really, telling

00:42:23.050 --> 00:42:27.100
stories and the storytelling
power of food.

00:42:27.100 --> 00:42:28.350
But obviously, this
all exists.

00:42:28.350 --> 00:42:33.990
I mean, the Holy Communion was
mentioned, Thanksgiving, the

00:42:33.990 --> 00:42:36.720
way we interact with
our wedding cake.

00:42:36.720 --> 00:42:38.370
The actual taste of
the wedding cake,

00:42:38.370 --> 00:42:39.420
there's not much to it.

00:42:39.420 --> 00:42:43.020
But we all remember it as the
most amazing taste we had.

00:42:43.020 --> 00:42:45.580
Because it actually
eaten in context.

00:42:45.580 --> 00:42:48.140
It's how all the other
senses are involved.

00:42:48.140 --> 00:42:50.400
It's visually, there's so
much presentations.

00:42:50.400 --> 00:42:53.200
But insider it's just an
over-sweetened sponge.

00:42:53.200 --> 00:42:57.390
And the fantastic feast at the
end of Eid as well, after

00:42:57.390 --> 00:43:00.510
fasting during Ramadan.

00:43:00.510 --> 00:43:02.910
So food is a manifestation
of our longings.

00:43:02.910 --> 00:43:05.240
But I really believe it is
a vocabulary of our life.

00:43:05.240 --> 00:43:08.205
Because we really remember
last Christmas.

00:43:08.205 --> 00:43:09.918
Oh, that was when we were
in Italy and we

00:43:09.918 --> 00:43:10.420
had this great food.

00:43:10.420 --> 00:43:14.590
We use food as vocabulary, as
punctuation to our life.

00:43:14.590 --> 00:43:17.100
 

00:43:17.100 --> 00:43:20.520
My favourite food ritual
is the birthday cake.

00:43:20.520 --> 00:43:23.460
Because for me, it is incredibly
universal.

00:43:23.460 --> 00:43:24.580
It only appeared--

00:43:24.580 --> 00:43:28.015
correct me if I'm wrong-- in the
last 60 years worldwide.

00:43:28.015 --> 00:43:31.090
And the taste sensation of
eating a birthday cake is an

00:43:31.090 --> 00:43:33.650
ordinary over-sweetened
sponge.

00:43:33.650 --> 00:43:35.650
But the eating of it
is a masterminded

00:43:35.650 --> 00:43:37.610
multi-sensory spectacle.

00:43:37.610 --> 00:43:41.290
The anticipation, it has been
baked especially for us.

00:43:41.290 --> 00:43:42.200
The light is dimmed.

00:43:42.200 --> 00:43:44.940
Candles are lit, one symbolising
each year of our

00:43:44.940 --> 00:43:48.180
life, another chorus of
Happy Birthday to You.

00:43:48.180 --> 00:43:51.050
We close our eyes, make a
wish, blow out the fire.

00:43:51.050 --> 00:43:54.040
The smell of the smoky wax,
our wish will come true.

00:43:54.040 --> 00:43:55.120
Oh, how delicious.

00:43:55.120 --> 00:43:58.350
Suddenly, we are four
years old again.

00:43:58.350 --> 00:44:01.040
So we have all those
10,000 taste buds

00:44:01.040 --> 00:44:02.410
to detect five tastes.

00:44:02.410 --> 00:44:06.090
But our mind really creates most
of our taste sensations.

00:44:06.090 --> 00:44:09.220
So eating is a fully immersive
experience.

00:44:09.220 --> 00:44:11.890
And how do they interplay?

00:44:11.890 --> 00:44:15.930
And what happens if the sense
of smell interplays with a

00:44:15.930 --> 00:44:17.250
sense of hearing and it creates

00:44:17.250 --> 00:44:19.700
something like no other?

00:44:19.700 --> 00:44:23.480
So I was looking into how can we
enhance these experiences?

00:44:23.480 --> 00:44:25.880
And then I came across
Charles Spence.

00:44:25.880 --> 00:44:27.935
I got really excited that,
actually, there is research

00:44:27.935 --> 00:44:32.090
done in exactly that very field
I find so fascinating,

00:44:32.090 --> 00:44:33.750
which gives me, obviously,
most of the

00:44:33.750 --> 00:44:36.140
motivation for my practise.

00:44:36.140 --> 00:44:41.370
So I ended up collaborating on
a multi-sensory menu which I

00:44:41.370 --> 00:44:44.350
served up for one month
at the House of Wolf.

00:44:44.350 --> 00:44:46.440
This is a little excerpt
of the menu.

00:44:46.440 --> 00:44:48.760
And it really plays with the
findings Charles mentioned

00:44:48.760 --> 00:44:52.030
before, the fact that so much
of our taste experience is

00:44:52.030 --> 00:44:55.400
based on our hearing, and
playing with it and showing it

00:44:55.400 --> 00:44:58.130
to people in the way, obviously
not meaning that

00:44:58.130 --> 00:45:03.570
people should eat forevermore
with headphones and things,

00:45:03.570 --> 00:45:06.320
just to really draw attention
to the way we eat and to

00:45:06.320 --> 00:45:10.240
enhance our dining experience in
the way that we assess it.

00:45:10.240 --> 00:45:14.170
So science offers me a huge
toolbox to play with.

00:45:14.170 --> 00:45:15.910
It's fantastic because
it is almost like

00:45:15.910 --> 00:45:16.820
the artist's palette.

00:45:16.820 --> 00:45:20.530
And I just grab and take it
from all different things,

00:45:20.530 --> 00:45:24.310
from how much taste is in a
colour to touch and taste.

00:45:24.310 --> 00:45:31.370
And there are specially-made
dining utensils where I carved

00:45:31.370 --> 00:45:37.280
fish-fork-style endings into
tree branches to really draw

00:45:37.280 --> 00:45:41.320
home the wild nature of eating
meat and to grow it back to

00:45:41.320 --> 00:45:44.510
the over-modulated fork.

00:45:44.510 --> 00:45:47.540
The one thing I find most
fascinating is sound, and how

00:45:47.540 --> 00:45:51.450
to really modulate the
experience of food through

00:45:51.450 --> 00:45:52.590
certain sounds.

00:45:52.590 --> 00:45:55.350
I mean, I heard that you can
actually modulate the taste of

00:45:55.350 --> 00:45:59.630
food from sweet to bitter by
changing certain frequencies.

00:45:59.630 --> 00:46:01.260
I thought that was really
fascinating.

00:46:01.260 --> 00:46:03.150
So I started to play
around with that.

00:46:03.150 --> 00:46:06.420
So I came up with this sonic
cake pop, where I gave people

00:46:06.420 --> 00:46:08.230
a cake pop and a lollipop
stick and

00:46:08.230 --> 00:46:10.460
then a telephone number.

00:46:10.460 --> 00:46:12.560
So people could ring a
certain phone number.

00:46:12.560 --> 00:46:15.940
And then they could literally
dial a taste.

00:46:15.940 --> 00:46:18.270
And they could decide it.

00:46:18.270 --> 00:46:19.860
So diners were given
a number to call.

00:46:19.860 --> 00:46:21.530
And they were prompted
to press one for

00:46:21.530 --> 00:46:23.680
sweet, two for bitter.

00:46:23.680 --> 00:46:25.120
And obviously, it does work.

00:46:25.120 --> 00:46:27.740
But it's fantastic where it
could go, whether we go one

00:46:27.740 --> 00:46:30.230
day into a coffee shop and
we can have the perfect

00:46:30.230 --> 00:46:31.870
customised coffee,
I don't know.

00:46:31.870 --> 00:46:33.760
It would be fantastic.

00:46:33.760 --> 00:46:36.670
So the experience of flavour is
the integration of taste,

00:46:36.670 --> 00:46:39.770
touch and smell.

00:46:39.770 --> 00:46:41.140
But flavour conjures memories.

00:46:41.140 --> 00:46:44.550
And I really am incredibly
fascinated into involuntary

00:46:44.550 --> 00:46:47.450
memory, which obviously is known
as, as well, the Proust

00:46:47.450 --> 00:46:49.200
phenomenon.

00:46:49.200 --> 00:46:52.360
I won't read this out, but
obviously, most of us would

00:46:52.360 --> 00:46:55.170
have come across Proust or the
episode of the Madeleines,

00:46:55.170 --> 00:47:00.610
when almost just by eating and
dunking a Madeleine into warm

00:47:00.610 --> 00:47:03.340
tea, he is completely
transported

00:47:03.340 --> 00:47:05.280
back into his past.

00:47:05.280 --> 00:47:06.130
He's not remembering it.

00:47:06.130 --> 00:47:08.510
He's not thinking, oh, I'm going
to have a Madeleine like

00:47:08.510 --> 00:47:10.200
I used to have when I
was 12 years old.

00:47:10.200 --> 00:47:11.180
But he's dunking it.

00:47:11.180 --> 00:47:13.730
And suddenly, it's almost
like human time travel.

00:47:13.730 --> 00:47:14.470
He's just there.

00:47:14.470 --> 00:47:17.540
And he's there again.

00:47:17.540 --> 00:47:20.710
So obviously, there are
different kinds of memory.

00:47:20.710 --> 00:47:22.860
But involuntary memory is not
just an unearthing of the

00:47:22.860 --> 00:47:25.470
past, but a reliving of the
past as the present.

00:47:25.470 --> 00:47:28.490
We grasp the past
as the present.

00:47:28.490 --> 00:47:30.695
So maybe Proust was
a neuroscientist.

00:47:30.695 --> 00:47:33.390
I mean, there are different
books on literature out there.

00:47:33.390 --> 00:47:34.410
I doubt it very much.

00:47:34.410 --> 00:47:36.630
But science is not the only
path to knowledge.

00:47:36.630 --> 00:47:39.520
Where the brain is concerned,
sometimes art was their first.

00:47:39.520 --> 00:47:42.680
So there's a French chef who
first discovered umami.

00:47:42.680 --> 00:47:46.510
And with Cezanne and his
wonderful way of looking at

00:47:46.510 --> 00:47:49.210
the world, obviously
this influence in

00:47:49.210 --> 00:47:51.220
neuroscience as well.

00:47:51.220 --> 00:47:54.440
Picasso once said, we all know
that art is not truth.

00:47:54.440 --> 00:47:56.660
Art is a lie that makes
us realise truth.

00:47:56.660 --> 00:47:59.080
But just imagine where we'll
go when we bridge those two

00:47:59.080 --> 00:48:02.240
cultures together.

00:48:02.240 --> 00:48:03.715
Because I really believe
food is us.

00:48:03.715 --> 00:48:07.550
And that's how we remember
our travels and our

00:48:07.550 --> 00:48:09.530
family and who we are.

00:48:09.530 --> 00:48:11.370
And eating is the most
intimate way we

00:48:11.370 --> 00:48:12.680
interact with our brain.

00:48:12.680 --> 00:48:14.938
So yeah, thank you.

00:48:14.938 --> 00:48:16.850
[APPLAUSE]

00:48:16.850 --> 00:48:18.100
Wonderful.

00:48:18.100 --> 00:48:23.280
 

00:48:23.280 --> 00:48:24.190
Thank you Caroline.

00:48:24.190 --> 00:48:27.570
I think that's a wonderful
illustration of just how art

00:48:27.570 --> 00:48:31.520
and science can be not just
working side by side, but

00:48:31.520 --> 00:48:34.980
genuinely interacting, where
each really benefits from the

00:48:34.980 --> 00:48:36.580
contribution the other makes.

00:48:36.580 --> 00:48:41.030
And that kind of reciprocal
working where we learn

00:48:41.030 --> 00:48:44.500
something in the science from
Caroline's work and from the

00:48:44.500 --> 00:48:47.140
experiments that she puts
people through.

00:48:47.140 --> 00:48:49.630
But she's also using it to
create art and to create

00:48:49.630 --> 00:48:51.170
experiences for people.

00:48:51.170 --> 00:48:54.760
I should also tell you that the
Proust phenomenon is one

00:48:54.760 --> 00:48:59.160
of the big topics of another
AHRC-funded network, the

00:48:59.160 --> 00:49:00.030
Memory Network.

00:49:00.030 --> 00:49:02.180
And I'm very much hoping you'll
come and join them and

00:49:02.180 --> 00:49:04.300
talk more about Proust.

