I think there are all sorts
of elements of social

01:02:34.130 --> 01:02:38.300
conditioning about how you enjoy
it, whether you should

01:02:38.300 --> 01:02:42.970
enjoy it, with whom you
should enjoy it.

01:02:42.970 --> 01:02:47.166
It's quite hard to
hang onto that

01:02:47.166 --> 01:02:48.890
sort of question directly.

01:02:48.890 --> 01:02:52.130
Because there's so many possible
contexts in which

01:02:52.130 --> 01:02:56.740
food can be consumed and which
it can be prepared.

01:02:56.740 --> 01:03:01.145
There are, quite often, within a
society, different cuisines.

01:03:01.145 --> 01:03:04.890
And if I was an anthropologist I
would expect to see an elite

01:03:04.890 --> 01:03:08.470
cuisine with male chefs, if
you like, and a demotic

01:03:08.470 --> 01:03:12.670
cuisine, perhaps run by the
women doing the cooking.

01:03:12.670 --> 01:03:16.250
But they provide different
philosophies really, for why

01:03:16.250 --> 01:03:17.450
and how food is eaten.

01:03:17.450 --> 01:03:19.750
So it's quite hard to see
a division between

01:03:19.750 --> 01:03:21.080
one world and another.

01:03:21.080 --> 01:03:24.160
Because I suspect there are a
very great many experiences in

01:03:24.160 --> 01:03:25.680
these different worlds.

01:03:25.680 --> 01:03:29.530
You might also expect that when
people are hungry, when

01:03:29.530 --> 01:03:32.590
people are very close to
starvation, that if there is

01:03:32.590 --> 01:03:34.480
an edible and nutritious
source of food

01:03:34.480 --> 01:03:35.170
around they'll eat it.

01:03:35.170 --> 01:03:37.190
But there are parts of the world
where people are in that

01:03:37.190 --> 01:03:39.910
condition and manioc is
locally available.

01:03:39.910 --> 01:03:41.680
And they won't eat manioc.

01:03:41.680 --> 01:03:45.010
Whereas if you go to South
America, people will have it

01:03:45.010 --> 01:03:46.330
as a food of choice.

01:03:46.330 --> 01:03:47.750
They'll have it and
want to eat it.

01:03:47.750 --> 01:03:51.170
So it's very interesting that
that discrimination of what

01:03:51.170 --> 01:03:52.860
you will find acceptable
or not still

01:03:52.860 --> 01:03:54.570
remains even under extremes.

01:03:54.570 --> 01:03:55.701
Caroline?

01:03:55.701 --> 01:03:59.140
Yeah, I just wanted to say, or
add to that, that even when

01:03:59.140 --> 01:04:01.480
you're hungry, I think
food is never just

01:04:01.480 --> 01:04:03.310
reduced to pure nutrition.

01:04:03.310 --> 01:04:06.250
And I went to Pakistan
into some camps.

01:04:06.250 --> 01:04:12.000
And when people are very, very
hungry they even put more

01:04:12.000 --> 01:04:15.720
emphasis on the eating
experience.

01:04:15.720 --> 01:04:19.280
And then so many fantastic
literature has been written

01:04:19.280 --> 01:04:22.390
during wartime hunger years,
where people go on about the

01:04:22.390 --> 01:04:23.450
absence of something.

01:04:23.450 --> 01:04:26.220
I mean, often it's a very common
tool in literature.

01:04:26.220 --> 01:04:28.870
The absence of food, of
something is described by

01:04:28.870 --> 01:04:32.900
describing the foods you had in
the plenty or longing, or

01:04:32.900 --> 01:04:34.280
wishing for a certain food.

01:04:34.280 --> 01:04:37.450
So I think because obviously,
dealing with eating

01:04:37.450 --> 01:04:39.250
experiences where there is a lot
of foods, like oh, you're

01:04:39.250 --> 01:04:41.080
playing with food and people
are going hungry.

01:04:41.080 --> 01:04:44.250
How does that coincide?

01:04:44.250 --> 01:04:49.920
But I think people always have
the right for eating

01:04:49.920 --> 01:04:50.230
experience.

01:04:50.230 --> 01:04:52.870
And food is so much more than
just nutrition, even when

01:04:52.870 --> 01:04:53.465
people don't have any.

01:04:53.465 --> 01:04:54.950
Even when people are hungry.

01:04:54.950 --> 01:04:56.780
One last question, I think
we have time for

01:04:56.780 --> 01:04:58.260
here, in the middle.

01:04:58.260 --> 01:05:01.790
Different people have talked
about different conditions

01:05:01.790 --> 01:05:04.960
under which eating
is taking place.

01:05:04.960 --> 01:05:08.870
Has anybody done anything
objectively with

01:05:08.870 --> 01:05:10.190
regard to the brain?

01:05:10.190 --> 01:05:16.740
For instance, doing functional
MRI studies?

01:05:16.740 --> 01:05:17.980
Yes.

01:05:17.980 --> 01:05:20.460
Under all these different
sorts of eatings?

01:05:20.460 --> 01:05:24.330
There is a lot of
study coming.

01:05:24.330 --> 01:05:26.430
Certainly not as much as
you'd have on some

01:05:26.430 --> 01:05:27.630
of the other senses.

01:05:27.630 --> 01:05:30.250
And part of the problem is that,
as you may know, when

01:05:30.250 --> 01:05:34.630
you're in an MRI scanner and you
want to do FMRI you have

01:05:34.630 --> 01:05:36.350
to keep very still.

01:05:36.350 --> 01:05:37.440
So it's very difficult.

01:05:37.440 --> 01:05:39.970
If you've got them chewing
you're probably going to blur

01:05:39.970 --> 01:05:42.340
those nice lovely pictures
where you see bits of the

01:05:42.340 --> 01:05:43.215
brain lighting up.

01:05:43.215 --> 01:05:46.100
There have been two studies that
I'm very interested in

01:05:46.100 --> 01:05:52.110
where they were studying
sommeliers identifying wines.

01:05:52.110 --> 01:05:53.660
Now, it's a very uncomfortable
experience.

01:05:53.660 --> 01:05:54.510
You're lying on your back.

01:05:54.510 --> 01:05:56.650
You have a tube inserted
into your mouth.

01:05:56.650 --> 01:05:57.850
And its directing liquid.

01:05:57.850 --> 01:06:00.210
And you're told just to let the
liquid go in and try not

01:06:00.210 --> 01:06:02.150
to do too much swallowing.

01:06:02.150 --> 01:06:07.120
Nonetheless, nonetheless, under
those conditions the

01:06:07.120 --> 01:06:09.050
results are very interesting.

01:06:09.050 --> 01:06:11.660
Because they answered the
following questions--

01:06:11.660 --> 01:06:17.410
who do you think uses more of
their cortical regions?

01:06:17.410 --> 01:06:19.980
Who uses more of the brain
when they're trying to

01:06:19.980 --> 01:06:21.490
identify a wine?

01:06:21.490 --> 01:06:24.380
The expert or the novice?

01:06:24.380 --> 01:06:25.630
Any guesses?

01:06:25.630 --> 01:06:27.500
 

01:06:27.500 --> 01:06:30.970
So it's the expert who uses less
of the brain because they

01:06:30.970 --> 01:06:32.170
know exactly what to use.

01:06:32.170 --> 01:06:34.370
And the rest of us, maybe
trying to use everything

01:06:34.370 --> 01:06:36.100
that's in our field.

01:06:36.100 --> 01:06:40.360
Second question, how much of the
brain is active in either

01:06:40.360 --> 01:06:44.120
the expert or the novice
when tasting water?

01:06:44.120 --> 01:06:47.760
And the answer is huge amounts
in the expert.

01:06:47.760 --> 01:06:50.370
Even when they're tasting water
they can't turn off that

01:06:50.370 --> 01:06:52.250
capacity to evaluate
and assess.

01:06:52.250 --> 01:06:55.130
And the final question that
some of this research

01:06:55.130 --> 01:06:58.490
addresses is who gets
most pleasure, the

01:06:58.490 --> 01:07:02.910
sommelier or the novice?

01:07:02.910 --> 01:07:03.950
The novice?

01:07:03.950 --> 01:07:06.960
It's the sommelier.

01:07:06.960 --> 01:07:10.080
And that's why we do the
science, because the answers

01:07:10.080 --> 01:07:11.090
are surprising.

01:07:11.090 --> 01:07:14.380
So yes, there is
some FMRI done.

01:07:14.380 --> 01:07:15.910
Thank you all very much.

01:07:15.910 --> 01:07:17.596
Let's go and taste.

